         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">After Ānanda having said, So it will be, Arhat! and thereupon had come to the potter, he says: || In the C.</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">So it will be, arhat!  (cf 24)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>624</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1944"/><citedRange>24</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:ogihara2010"/><citedRange>170-171</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1991"/><citedRange>23</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">-tune: || The Buddha, the master, Śākyamuni, [our] protection and [our] hope, is tormented by sickness from the wind-disease, o Bṛhaddyuti! Warm water</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Der Buddha, der Meister, Śākyamuni, [unser] Schutz [und unsere] Hoffnung, wird von Erkrankung durch Windkrankheit gequält, o Bṛhaddyuti!</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">The Buddha, the master, [our] protection [and our] hope, Śākyamuni, is tormented by sickness from the wind-disease, oh Bṛhaddyuti!</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>256</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2 #a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>317</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>31</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>61</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1981"/><citedRange>487</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>168</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">for bathing and oil of sesame for anointing he requires. You are trustworthy to the Buddha as one longing for merit, serve him in this. 1.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3 #a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1991"/><citedRange>14</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>218</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>99</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1979a"/><citedRange>244</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>73</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>52</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>58</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">by hearing the name of the Buddha on his entire body his hair stood high on Bṛhaddyuti. Quickly, quickly he arose</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4 #a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1958a"/><citedRange>157</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">from his bed and (with tears) in [his] eyes and hands folded he says with great reverence to Ānanda: speak, speak, o worthy Ānanda</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1991"/><citedRange>14</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(Who is he that) is called (Buddha?) || In the A.-tune: || I heard the name of the Buddha; my mind felt longing for virtue</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(and my) heart (is filled) with joy [in thinking]: The Buddha, the master, who by his knowledge has awoken as it were in the world having fallen asleep under the hindrances,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>202</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">([him] I will see). Tell me, oh Ānanda, who is the Buddha Lord? Like what is that? What does he tell about that? Does he give me a command about that?</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>244</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>74</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">a name unheard in [my] births over [many] kalpas, I have heard, therefore I ask you: who is that? What does the ‘Buddha’ mean?</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Einen durch Kalpas hindurch in [meinen] Geburten nicht gehörten Namen hörte ich; deshalb frage ich dich: "Wer [ist] das, was [bedeutet] das: 'Buddha'?"</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">I heard a name [I have] not heard in [my] births for [long] kalpas; therefore I ask you: "Who [is] this? what [is the meaning of] this: 'Buddha'?"</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>377</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">1. Ānanda speaks: It is even thus: the glorious one, the one having come in this way, the Arhat, the one truly knowing all Dharmas</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>50</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">together, the one endowed with morality and knowledge, the one knowing the world, the unsurpassable, the one leading those to be reined</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">by a rein, the teacher of gods and humans, the Buddha, the glorious, the one who in morality, energy, meditation and know(ledge surpasses) all beings</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6 txt:m-a21#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>469</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice></p>
